passages.text: China (PRC) | Consumer Staples

WLY (Wuliangye) reported 2Q25 results after market close on Aug-27 HKT.2Q25 earnings miss (vs our expectations) likely shows that distributors face more pressure from intensifying macro and policy headwinds, on top of WLY's weak channel and product pricing management. We cut WLY's structural sales growth forecasts and lower PT to RMB80. Reiterate Underperform.

***2Q25 results missed our expectations:** 2Q25 EBIT/net profit came in down 10%/8% YoY,respectively, marking the worst declines since 2Q16. We note that Moutai managed to grow 2Q25 net profit by 5% YoY.
(1) Macro: Intensifying consumption downgrade. Our checks indicate a new round of consumption downgrade starting in June 2025.

(2) Policy: The "banquet ban" remains strict. We note that local governments tend to intensify the central government's policies. Despite marginal loosening in the central government's attitude, we observed very strict bans enforced, especially in provinces like Shandong and Henan.

(3) e-commerce: Instant retail is the latest disruption to baijiu prices. It is increasingly difficult for baijiu companies to manage their retail prices, starting from the Double-11 promotion in 2024. In 2024, live-stream e-commerce companies bought significant WLY inventory from WLY distributors and sold them to consumers at more than 20% discount to attract traffic.Recently, instant retailers like Meituan, started offering liquor delivery services. To attract traffic and acquire new users, we noticed instant retailers selling WLY at 20% discount vs. offline retail prices.

***WLY not tackling problems so far, and distributors are no longer hiding their frustration:** Distributors who seek a rescue plan from WLY are met with disappointment, based on our checks. WLY is not providing additional rebates, cash flow support (delaying distributors' payments) or inventory buyback. In response to the meager support, we observed WLY's larger distributors cutting ordags and smaller distributors exiting the market by selling their WLY inventory to e-commerce platforms. More importantly, we believe distributors are expressing more doubt about WLY's brand equity. The sharp price disruption from e-commerce and a surge in fake WLY make WLY less suitable as gifts.
In the meantime, WLY management is spending more resources to branch into new categories like craft beer.

***Revisions.** We lower our sales growth forecasts for 2025E-27E, modeling structurally slower growth. This is to reflect WLY's deteriorating channel management and brand equity. We did not change our GPM or opex-to-sales forecasts significantly as we anticipate limited support from WLY headquarters to distributors. We cut our DCF-based PT accordingly to RMB80.

Wuliangye reforms have been disappointing, in our view. As distributors' frustration mount, we expect Wuliangye's control on distribution, pricing, and branding to deteriorate. In the near term, we observe more challenges from macro, policy and the emergence of e- commerce. e- commerce is now an important distribution channel for baijiu, and it is causing significant disruption in the industry, in our view.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

Distribution margin for Standard Wuliangye remains limited. Worse- than- expected macro environment Demand for premium liquor ceases to grow, with steady consumer sentiment. Management continues to implement reforms to enhance branding and distribution channels as planned. DCF- based price target of RMB80.

Macroeconomic growth is better than expected. Helped by strong consumer sentiment, premium liquor demand growth accelerates. An increasing number of consumers trade up to premium liquor. Retail price increases significantly on improving branding and Moutai price hike. Penetration rate at retail end improves due to strengthened distribution channels. Classic Wuliangye enjoys strong demand. The company launches more super premium products with higher volume. DCF- based price target of RMB130.

Macroeconomic growth slows significantly. Consumer income growth decelerates, and consumers trade down to cheaper liquor. Management changes, and reform plans are suspended. Channel profit turns negative due to increasing competition and weak demand. DCF- based price target of RMB40.

Top Material Issue(s): 1) Food safety and product quality are most important for F&B manufacturers. The company has strengthened mechanisms and upgraded the management system; added indicators for plasticizers, bisphenol A, solids, heavy metals and implemented stricter food safety standards than international limits to the testing process. 2) Environment protection is also a key issue for baijiu manufacturers as they use water as a major resource and impact the ecosystem around their factories. Natural gas, water, slag, green environment, carbon and other ecological factors all matter. 3) Corruption is an issue that high-end baijiu companies need to face.
Company Target(s): 1) To create a "zero- carbon liquor enterprise". 2) Comply with CASS- CSR4.0

Q5o Mgmt: 1) How do you balance ecological conservation with capacity expansion plans? 2) How much environmental protection cost do you expect to incur in the medium- to- long term? 3) Do you have any plans to set a medium- to long- term timeline for environment management issues? What are the obstacles to this?

Wuliangye Yibin is one of the major liquor manufacturers in China. Wuliangye is a typical representative of China's strong aromatic liquor, with a history dating back to the Ming Dynasty. It owns China's oldest existing crypt- type fermentation pits group passed from the Ming Dynasty. The company has a full series of liquor products covering the whole price range from low end to high end, with a key focus on 1+3 brand series. It has a nationwide distribution network in China. The company was listed on the Shenzhen Stock Exchange in 1998.

We value Wuliangye Yibin based on a fundamental DCF approach (CoE \(9.5\%\) , TG \(1\%\) ). Upside risks include a rapid increase in the wholesale price of the Standard Wuliangye, giving distributors better margins, faster expansion of new products, as well as strong growth in e- commerce.
We value Kweichow Moutai based on a fundamental DCF approach. Downside risks include unexpected channel destocking, macro slowdown, and food safety issues.

We have a Buy rating and PT of HKD139 based on P/E valuation. Risks include: (1) intensifying competitive landscape in food delivery, leading to aggressive subsidies and marketing efforts; (2) user experience is impaired on poor merchant service quality and unreliable user feedback; and (3) new initiatives incur significant losses and affect overall operating results.

Buy - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of \(15\%\) or more within a 12- month period. Hold - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of plus \(15\%\) or minus \(10\%\) within a 12- month period. Underperform - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of minus \(10\%\) or less within a 12- month period.

The expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) for Buy rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10 is 20\%\) or more within a 12- month period as these companies are typically more volatile than the overall stock market. For Hold rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10, the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is plus or minus 20% within a 12- month period. For Underperform rated securities with an average security price consistently below\) 10, the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is minus 20% or less within a 12- month period.

Jefferies Franchise Picks include stock selections from among the best stock ideas from our equity analysts over a 12 month period. Stock selection is based on fundamental analysis and may take into account other factors such as analyst conviction, differentiated analysis, a favorable risk/reward ratio and investment themes that Jefferies analysts are recommending. Jefferies Franchise Picks will include only Buy rated stocks and the number can vary depending on analyst recommendations for inclusion. Stocks will be added as new opportunities arise and removed when the reason for inclusion changes, the stock has met its desired return, if it is no longer rated Buy and/or if it triggers a stop loss. Stocks having 120 day volatility in the bottom quartile of S&P stocks will continue to have a 15% stop loss, and the remainder will have a 20% stop. Franchise Picks are not intended to represent a recommended portfolio of stocks and is not sector based, but we may note where we believe a Pick falls within an investment style such as growth or value.
